	abstract = {The fifth-generation (5G) and emerging sixthgeneration (6G) networks, are slowly but surely becoming an indispensable part of human life. However, their complexity creates a significant learning challenge when introducing their security concepts into Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics (STEM) curricula. Thus, there is a need for domain-specific telecommunication security education. In this paper, a concise, modular framework is proposed, utilizing the capabilities of Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI). By combining AI-based threat detection examples with XAI visualizations, students learn how intelligent systems identify suspicious activity and understand the reasoning behind these decisions. This curriculum format, which prioritizes conceptual learning, can be easily integrated to interdisciplinary STEM contexts. The pedagogical rationale is presented, following an outline of the main modules of an AI-enabled 5G/6G network security course. Moreover, a prototype scenario simplifying an AI model for educational purposes is provided. Finally, integration possibilities, implementation challenges, and directions for future work are discussed. © 2025 IEEE.},
