	abstract = {The swift emergence of digital technologies is radically reconfiguring teaching approaches, tools, and goals. Informatics, both as curriculum area and certain set of tools, has itself become the core foundation of the learning process instead of a subsidiary aspect. Artificial intelligence (AI) has drawn increasing attention in the last few years for the potential to individualize learning, to facilitate the automation of summative assessments, and to enable innovative types of supportive teaching. But embedding AI into teaching is not just a technological challenge but also raises pedagogical and psychological questions. Of particular importance is the question of how students see and respond to AI-particularly how these attitudes change in response to AI being explicitly integrated in learning. This research seeks to investigate the adoption of A I in a learning environment within the organization of a university course. In this study, artificial intelligence was applied to solve various tasks within the Numerical Mathematics course of the BSc program. The assigned problems were solved using AI tools, and the resulting solutions were analyzed together with the students. We examined the correctness of the AI-generated solutions and measured students' attitudes toward AI both before and after the experiment. For the measurement, we employed the attitude scale developed by Grassini. The results obtained from the preand post-experiment assessments were compared using statistical methods. According to our findings, certain components of students' perceptions of AI changed significantly during the experiment. © 2025 IEEE.},
